<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Nugget service</p>
    <h2>Why nugget ice machines fail differently than cube or flake.</h2>

    <p>Nugget ice (soft, hollow, chewable "Sonic-style" ice) has become hospitality's favorite ice type. Hospitals adopted it for patient comfort (easier to chew, gentler on dental work). Premium fast-casual restaurants (Chick-fil-A made it famous, but it's industry-wide now) use it for beverages. Premium beverage programs use it where cube ice would chip cocktails.</p>

    <p>We service nugget ice machines across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. Three dominant brands cover roughly 85% of LA market: <strong>Scotsman Brilliance series</strong> (Ali Group, with N0422, N0622, N0922 sizes by lb/day, the original "Sonic ice" architecture), <strong>Hoshizaki FS Sliver Nugget</strong> (Hoshizaki's premium answer with FS-1000MWH and variants), <strong>Manitowoc R-Series</strong> (Welbilt with RNS-0385A and RNS-0820A nugget machines). Plus <strong>Follett</strong> medical-grade nugget machines common in hospitals.</p>

    <p><strong>Architecture is similar to flake ice</strong> with an auger inside a cylindrical evaporator drum. Water freezes on the inner drum surface, the auger continuously rotates and scrapes ice off, <strong>but with a critical difference: nugget machines have an extrusion mechanism that compresses the scraped ice into nugget shape before discharge</strong>. This adds another mechanical wear point on top of flake-style architecture, and it's the differentiator that drives nugget-specific service skills.</p>

    <p>EPA 608 Universal plus R-290 certified (post-2020 nugget machines transitioning to R-290 hydrocarbon refrigerant; Scotsman, Hoshizaki, and Manitowoc all transitioning). BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. <a href="/credentials/epa-certified/">EPA 608 verifiable.</a></p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Failure modes</p>
    <h2>Typical nugget ice machine failures, in order of frequency.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Nugget machines combine flake-style auger drive with a nugget-specific extrusion mechanism. The failure mix reflects both architectures plus standard ice-machine items (water, refrigerant, condenser).</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Auger gear reducer wear (year 6 to 9).</strong> Most common nugget-specific failure. Heavy mechanical load on the auger gearbox. Symptoms: noise increases, nugget production decreases, sometimes seizure. $580 to $880.</li>
      <li><strong>Extrusion mechanism wear (year 7 to 10).</strong> Nugget-specific (NOT on flake or cube machines). Compresses scraped ice into nugget shape. Wear causes slush instead of proper nugget. $480 to $780 typical replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Auger motor failure (year 8 to 12).</strong> Main drive motor.</li>
      <li><strong>Drive shaft seal wear (year 5 to 7).</strong> Water leakage from the machine bottom; food-safety concern in healthcare and bar environments.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale buildup on evaporator drum interior.</strong> Same root cause as cube and flake. Cleaning resolves.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve.</strong> Replacement $260 to $420.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak.</strong> EPA 608 leak repair before recharge. Post-2020 R-290 systems require R-290 cert.</li>
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor (air-cooled units).</strong> Typical 4 to 7 year coastal life.</li>
      <li><strong>Bin sensor failure.</strong> Overflow or empty errors.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor short-cycling.</strong> Refrigerant low, condenser fouled, or ambient overload from tight installation.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 BRAND-SPECIFIC NOTES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Brand notes</p>
    <h2>What we see by brand on nugget service calls.</h2>

    <p><strong>Scotsman Brilliance (Original "Sonic Ice" Architecture).</strong> N0422 (420 lb/day), N0622 (620 lb/day), N0922 (920 lb/day). Air-cooled (-A), water-cooled (W). Common in hospitality and premium fast-casual. Ali Group parts via Scotsman service network with 5 to 7 day standard ship.</p>

    <p><strong>Hoshizaki FS Sliver Nugget.</strong> FS-1000MWH (1,000 lb/day water-cooled). Hoshizaki's premium nugget answer. Service via Hoshizaki America Peachtree City distribution (4 to 7 day ship). Distinct architecture from Scotsman: same nugget output, different evaporator and extrusion design.</p>

    <p><strong>Manitowoc R-Series.</strong> RNS-0385A (385 lb/day) and RNS-0820A (820 lb/day). Welbilt parts network. Easy-Read display diagnostic system standard, which speeds up service substantially when the codes are read correctly first.</p>

    <p><strong>Follett Medical-Grade Nugget.</strong> Specifically designed for healthcare environments with sanitation and chain-of-custody requirements. Hospital procurement coordinates through facility managers. Common in cafeterias and patient-care wings.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Real repairs</p>
    <h2>Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five nugget ice machine jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, diagnosis, parts, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Hospital cafeteria in Pasadena · Scotsman Brilliance N0622A nugget (7 years, R-404A)</h3>
        <p>Auger noise plus nugget production reduced to slush. Diagnosed: extrusion mechanism wear (typical 7 to 10 year, slightly early due to heavy 24/7 hospital use). Replaced extrusion assembly. Nugget quality restored. Total: $120 plus $640 part plus 2.5 hours = $1,000.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Premium fast-casual restaurant in Beverly Hills · Manitowoc RNS-0820A nugget (5 years)</h3>
        <p>Easy-Read display showed E1 error code (water inlet fault). Replaced water inlet valve. Cleared error code. Total: $120 plus $290 part plus 1 hour = $410.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Bar in West Hollywood · Hoshizaki FS-1000MWH Sliver Nugget (8 years, R-404A)</h3>
        <p>Auger seizure. Diagnosed: gear reducer end-of-life plus auger motor showing wear (cascading failure typical at 8 years heavy bar use). Replaced both gear reducer and motor. Nugget production restored. Total: $120 plus $1,140 parts plus 4 hours = $1,640. 5+ years more service life expected.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Healthcare facility in Marina del Rey · Follett 7CI100A-S nugget medical-grade (11 years)</h3>
        <p>Drive shaft seal failure, water leaking from machine bottom. Diagnosed: seal wear (5 to 7 year typical; this 11-year unit was beyond expected life). Replaced seals. Hospital approved continued service vs replacement based on cabinet condition. Total: $120 plus $290 seals plus 2 hours = $560.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Cocktail bar in Santa Monica · Scotsman Brilliance N0422A nugget (6 years)</h3>
        <p>Refrigerant slow leak; machine had been needing top-off every 4 months (previous shop was violating EPA 608 by recharging without leak repair). EPA 608 leak detection, brazed evap joint repair, evacuated to 500 microns, recharged R-404A. Now compliant. Total: $120 plus $480 refrigerant plus $720 labor plus leak detection = $1,420.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
